    "text": "Erdős Problem #600: declared status 'open'. Formalized: no. Let $e(n,r)$ be minimal such that every graph on $n$ vertices with at least $e(n,r)$ edges, each edge contained in at least one triangle, must have an edge contained in at least $r$ triangles. Let $r\\geq 2$. Is it true that\\[e(n,r+1)-e(n,r)\\to \\infty\\]as $n\\to \\infty$? Is it true that\\[\\frac{e(n,r+1)}{e(n,r)}\\to 1\\]as $n\\to \\infty$? Prize: no. Tags: graph theory.",
